            <abstract id="ref8" label="Abstract">Fanny Simon (1903-1989) was a labor organizer, economist, and socialist. Simon taught at James Monroe High School in Brooklyn and in 1936 helped found the New York Teachers Guild. She helped found the Coalition of Labor Union Women and remained active in the Guild's successor, The United Federation of Teachers, serving on its Women's Rights Committee. The papers contain Simon's clippings and research notes on labor in Latin America, her travel diaries, correspondence, and manuscripts.</abstract>
            <langmaterial id="ref13" label="Language of Materials">Materials are primarily in English, with some Spanish.</langmaterial>
